  "prompt": "Is it forbidden in Islam to name your child Allah?",
  "response": "In Islam, the name \"Allah\" is considered sacred and unique to the Supreme Being, the Creator of the universe. It is not permissible to name a child \"Allah\" because it would imply equating a human being with the Divine, which is contrary to the core Islamic principle of **Tawheed** (the Oneness of God).\n\nIslamic teachings emphasize the importance of choosing meaningful and respectful names for children, but the name \"Allah\" is reserved exclusively for God. Instead, Muslims are encouraged to use names that reflect servitude or praise to Allah, such as **Abdullah** (servant of Allah) or **Abdur-Rahman** (servant of the Most Merciful).\n\nScholars unanimously agree that naming a child \"Allah\" is prohibited, as it could lead to misunderstanding or disrespect toward the sanctity of God's name.",
